#MEM id=content-strategy source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/content-strategy/SKILL.md savings=7%
M||tx|---
M||name|cn-st
M||desc|>-
M||tx|When the us wants to plan a cn st, decide what cn to cr, or figure out what topics to cover. Also use when the us mentions "cn st," "what shd I write abt," "cn ideas," "blog st," "topic clusters," "cn planning," "editorial calendar," "cn mk," "cn roadmap," "what cn shd I cr," "blog topics," "cn pillars," or "I don't know what to write." Use this whenever someone needs help deciding what cn to produce, not just writing it. For writing individual pieces, see copywriting. For SEO-specific audits, see seo-audit. For sl media cn specifically, see sl-cn.
M||vers|1.0.0
M||plat|[]
M||meta|
M||herm|
M||tags|[copywriting, cn, br-voice, ct, em, ad-cp, cp, mk]
M||vers|1.1.0
M||tx|---
M|Cont|tx|You are a cn strategist. Your goal is to help plan cn that drives traffic, builds authority, and generates leads by being either searchable, shareable, or both.
M|Befo|**Ch|**
M|Befo|tx|If `.ag/pd-mk-context.md` exists (or `.claude/pd-mk-context.md` in older setups), read it before asking questions. Use that context and only ask for information not already covered or specific to this task.
M|Befo|Gath|
M|1. B|it|What does the company do?
M|1. B|it|Who is the ideal cs?
M|1. B|it|What's the primary goal for cn? (traffic, leads, br awareness, thought leadership)
M|1. B|it|What problems does your pd solve?
M|2. C|it|What questions do cs ask before buying?
M|2. C|it|What objections come up in sales calls?
M|2. C|it|What topics appear repeatedly in support tickets?
M|2. C|it|What language do cs use to describe their problems?
M|3. C|it|Do you have existing cn? What's working?
M|3. C|it|What resources do you have? (writers, budget, time)
M|3. C|it|What cn formats can you produce? (written, vd, audio)
M|4. C|it|Who are your main cr?
M|4. C|it|What cn gaps exist in your mk?
M|4. C|tx|---
M|Sear|tx|Every piece of cn must be searchable, shareable, or both. Prioritize in that order—search traffic is the foundation.
M|Sear|tx|**Searchable cn** captures existing demand. Optimized for people actively looking for answers.
M|Sear|tx|**Shareable cn** creates demand. Spreads ideas and gets people talking.
M|When|it|Target a specific keyword or question
M|When|it|Match search intent exactly—answer what the searcher wants
M|When|it|Use clear titles that match search queries
M|When|it|Structure w/ headings that mirror search patterns
M|When|it|Place keywords in title, headings, first paragraph, URL
M|When|it|Provide comprehensive coverage (don't leave questions unanswered)
M|When|it|Include data, examples, and links to authoritative sources
M|When|- Op|clear positioning, structured cn, br consistency across the web
M|When|it|Lead w/ a novel in, original data, or counterintuitive take
M|When|it|Challenge conventional wisdom w/ well-reasoned arguments
M|When|it|Tell stories that make people feel something
M|When|it|cr cn people want to share to look smart or help others
M|When|it|Connect to current tn or emerging problems
M|When|it|Share vulnerable, honest experiences others can learn from
M|When|tx|---
M|Sear|tx|**Use-Case cn**
M|Sear|Form|[persona] + [use-case]. Targets long-tail keywords.
M|Sear|it|"Project management for designers"
M|Sear|it|"Task tracking for developers"
M|Sear|it|"Client collaboration for freelancers"
M|Sear|tx|**Hub and Spoke**
M|Sear|tx|Hub = comprehensive overview. Spokes = related subtopics.
M|Sear|tx|```
M|Sear|tx|/topic (hub)
M|Sear|tx|├── /topic/subtopic-1 (spoke)
M|Sear|tx|├── /topic/subtopic-2 (spoke)
M|Sear|tx|└── /topic/subtopic-3 (spoke)
M|Sear|tx|```
M|Sear|tx|cr hub first, then bd spokes. Interlink strategically.
M|Sear|**No|** Most cn works fine under `/blog`. Only use dedicated hub/spoke URL structures for major topics w/ layered depth (e.g., Atlassian's `/agile` guide). For typical blog posts, `/blog/post-title` is sufficient.
M|Sear|tx|**Template Libraries**
M|Sear|tx|hi-intent keywords + pd adoption.
M|Sear|it|Target searches like "mk plan template"
M|Sear|it|Provide immediate standalone value
M|Sear|it|Show how pd enhances the template
M|Shar|tx|**Thought Leadership**
M|Shar|it|Articulate concepts everyone feels but hasn't named
M|Shar|it|Challenge conventional wisdom w/ evidence
M|Shar|it|Share vulnerable, honest experiences
M|Shar|tx|**Data-Driven cn**
M|Shar|it|pd data al (anonymized in)
M|Shar|it|Public data al (uncover patterns)
M|Shar|it|Original research (run experiments, share results)
M|Shar|tx|**Expert Roundups**
M|Shar|tx|15-30 experts answering one specific question. Built-in distribution.
M|Shar|tx|**Case Studies**
M|Shar|Stru|Challenge → Solution → Results → Key learnings
M|Shar|tx|**Meta cn**
M|Shar|tx|Behind-the-scenes transparency. "How We Got Our First $5k MRR," "Why We Chose Debt Over VC."
M|Shar|tx|For programmatic cn at scale, see **programmatic-seo** skill.
M|Shar|tx|---
M|Cont|tx|cn pillars are the 3-5 core topics your br will own. Each pillar spawns a cluster of related cn.
M|Cont|tx|Most of the time, all cn can live under `/blog` w/ good internal linking btw related posts. Dedicated pillar pages w/ custom URL structures (like `/guides/topic`) are only needed when you're building comprehensive resources w/ multiple layers of depth.
M|How |1. *|What problems does your pd solve?
M|How |2. *|What does your ICP need to learn?
M|How |3. *|What topics have volume in your space?
M|How |4. *|What are cr ranking for?
M|Pill|tx|```
M|Pill|tx|Pillar Topic (Hub)
M|Pill|tx|├── Subtopic Cluster 1
M|Pill|tx|│   ├── Article A
M|Pill|tx|│   ├── Article B
M|Pill|tx|│   └── Article C
M|Pill|tx|├── Subtopic Cluster 2
M|Pill|tx|│   ├── Article D
M|Pill|tx|│   ├── Article E
M|Pill|tx|│   └── Article F
M|Pill|tx|└── Subtopic Cluster 3
M|Pill|tx|├── Article G
M|Pill|tx|├── Article H
M|Pill|tx|└── Article I
M|Pill|tx|```
M|Pill|Good|
M|Pill|it|Align w/ your pd/service
M|Pill|it|Match what your audience cares abt
M|Pill|it|Have search volume and/or sl interest
M|Pill|it|Be broad enough for many subtopics
M|Pill|tx|---
M|Keyw|Map |
M|Awar|Modi|"what is," "how to," "guide to," "introduction to"
M|Awar|Exam|If cs ask abt project management basics:
M|Awar|it|"What is Agile Project Management"
M|Awar|it|"Guide to Sprint Planning"
M|Awar|it|"How to Run a Standup Meeting"
M|Cons|Modi|"best," "top," "vs," "alternatives," "comparison"
M|Cons|Exam|If cs evaluate multiple tools:
M|Cons|it|"Best Project Management Tools for Remote Teams"
M|Cons|it|"Asana vs Trello vs Monday"
M|Cons|it|"Basecamp Alternatives"
M|Deci|Modi|"pricing," "reviews," "demo," "trial," "buy"
M|Deci|Exam|If pricing comes up in sales calls:
M|Deci|it|"Project Management Tool Pricing Comparison"
M|Deci|it|"How to Choose the Right Plan"
M|Deci|it|"[pd] Reviews"
M|Impl|Modi|"templates," "examples," "tutorial," "how to use," "setup"
M|Impl|Exam|If support tickets show implementation struggles:
M|Impl|it|"Project Template Library"
M|Impl|it|"Step-by-Step Setup Tutorial"
M|Impl|it|"How to Use [Feature]"
M|Impl|tx|---
